====================================================================================================
JxMake USB-GPIO Module
====================================================================================================

This firmware is written for ATmega32U4.

If you are using Arduino Leonardo or SparkFun Pro Micro, you will need to bring out the SS (PB.0)
and XCK (PD.5) pins manually.

If you are using Arduino Micro, you will need to bring out the XCK (PD.5) pin manually.

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

The hardware SPI       implementation uses the standard ATmega32U4 SPI   pins.
The hardware TWI       implementation uses the standard ATmega32U4 TWI   pins.
The hardware UART/USRT implementation uses the standard ATmega32U4 USART pins.

The software USRT      implementation uses the standard ATmega32U4 SPI pins
                       (TXD=MOSI; RXD=MISO; XCK=SCK; [n]CS=[n]SS)

Except for PB.4 and PB.5 which are used to control the TWI external pull-up resistors, the remaining
pins can be used as GPIOs.

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

When connected, this module will enumerate as two Virtual Serial Port:
    1. The first port is the primary port for performing most operations.
    2. The second port is the UART/USRT passthrough port. Its baudrate and data format can be
       configured using your operating system and programming language features, just like a typical
       serial port (but without the support for control signals such as RTS, CTS, and others). Note
       that the passthrough must be enabled (and disabled) via commands from the primary port.

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Please replace the default Caterina bootloader with the one from this directory:

    avrdude -c usbasp -p m32u4 -e -D -U flash:w:LUFA-111009_BootloaderCaterina_ATmega32U4_16MHz.hex:i

Please note that the command above might only work properly if the ISP signals from USBasp are
connected directly to the ISP signals of the MCU module using jumper cables.

====================================================================================================
